in library for loading configuration files into typesafe classes in a boilerplate-free way.\nREADME.md:4:Define your config using Kotlin data classes, and at startup Hoplite will read from one or more config files,\nREADME.md:19:  types, inline classes, uuids, nullable types, as well as popular Kotlin third party library types such\nREADME.md:364:When the config is resolved into Kotlin classes, a lookup will cascade or fall through one file to another in the order they were passed to the loader, until the first file that defines that key.\nREADME.md:558:| `Enums`                                 | Java and Kotlin enums are both supported. An instance of the defined Enum class will be created with the constant value given in config.                                                                    |\nREADME.md:573:| **Kotlin types**                        |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\nREADME.md:583:| **Kotlin stdlib types**                 |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\nREADME.md:739:It is quite common to output the resolved config at startup for reference when debugging. In this case, the default `toString` generated by Kotlin's data classes is very useful.\nREADME.md:776:Kotlin has support for what it calls inline classes which fulfil this need.\nREADME.md:977:| hoplite-datetime              | Provides decoders for [kotlinx datetime](https://github.com/Kotlin/kotlinx-datetime).                   |\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782693608766}]}
